Profile U.S. Marine Corps Staff Sgt. Eric Alva
space Major General Christopher Cortez (left), Commanding General, Marine Corps Recruiting Command, commends Staff Sgt. Eric Alva, the 2003 recipient of the Heroes and Heritage Award, for his strength and determination.
U.S. Marine Corps photo by Sgt.
Matt Griffin space
AUSTIN, Texas -- Less than four months ago, Staff Sgt. Eric Alva nearly died.
On March 21, while serving with the 3rd Battalion, 7th Marines in Iraq, Alva stepped on a landmine.
He broke his right arm and his right leg was damaged so badly it needed to be amputated.
However, his sufferings haven't dampened his mind and spirit.
This was obvious to all who saw Alva accept the Heroes and Heritage Award July 13, at the National Council of La Raza during a special salute to Hispanics military presentation.
Major General Christopher Cortez, commanding general of Marine Corps Recruiting Command in Quantico, Va., was on stage and presented Alva with his award.
"SSgt.
Alva is a credit to the Corps," said Maj. Gen. Christopher Cortez.
"We are grateful for his faithful service and proud to honor him today."
